will vary depending upon the person; that said, if one is lucky enough to have a clear vision for their future and a set of clearly defined goals. there is definitely personal happiness to be found in pursuing and achieving those goals.

Not everyone is sure what they want from life -- having clearly defined goals is not a given for every single person. For a person who does have personal and definitive goals, however, their life is provided a structure and meaning that informs their days and can lead to great personal happiness. Breaking goals down into smaller pieces provides an every day schedule and an escalating sense of accomplishment and self esteem; achieving things one sets out to do likewise adds to that sense of accomplishment and self esteem.

\nPeople who have clear goals may have a wide range of goals, from the professional to the personal -- perhaps one person wants to raise children, another wants to go to medical school, and a third wants to make partner at their law firm. All three of these goals are not accomplished all at once; they are accomplished in bits and pieces, by attending classes or stacking up accomplishments in the courtroom, or by pursuing a meaningful relationship with a partner who is a potential co-parent, or perhaps by pursuing conceiving or adopting on one's own.\n
No matter what the goal, the structure offered by having a series of smaller accomplishments leading to bigger accomplishments provides a life with structure and meaning.

If one doesn't have clearly defined goals, however, happiness can be less attainable and less clearly defined; one could argue that teaching children early in their education to identify their personal wants and values so that they can clearly define their goals may be an important part of early education and later happiness.
